Let's look at what makes surfaces

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
special. What makes surfaces
special is that the coordination

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
number is different at the surface
from what it is inside the material.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
What I am showing here is the free
surface of the material.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And here is one region of the
material where the atoms are lined

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:24.330
up in this manner.
And here is another region of the

00:05:24.330 --> 00:05:28.990
material where the atoms are lined
up in this manner,

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:33.660
because they grew from the melt
starting from different starting

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:38.330
points from different nuclei.
And, when they impinge, this plane

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:42.990
does not line up with this plane.
And there is a boundary along here.

00:05:42.990 --> 00:05:47.660
We have two types of surfaces here.
We have a free surface and we have

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:52.230
an internal surface.
I am going to talk about both of

00:05:52.230 --> 00:05:56.690
them. The thing they have in common
is that if we look at an atom down

00:05:56.690 --> 00:06:01.150
here in the center,
if this is an FCC structure,

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:05.610
an atom here in an FCC structure has
12 nearest neighbors.

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:10.070
An atom here at the free surface
cannot have 12 nearest neighbors.

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:14.530
It has fewer than 12 nearest
neighbors. And we know that systems

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:32.860
form bonds maximally to
lower their energy.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:25.200
Therefore, if I have fewer than the
maximum number of bonds,

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:43.666
this is not at as low an energy at
the free surface as it would be were

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:17.600
it inside the material.
Because at the free surface it has

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:23.800
fewer than 12 nearest neighbors.
That means that surfaces are higher

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:30.000
energy. They are higher energy
regions in the crystal.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:54.280
And that can be good or it can be
bad. If we want something high

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:58.570
energy that is good if we are
looking for catalysis.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:02.850
We will talk about catalysis later,
but catalysis occurs at the free

00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:07.140
surface. By definition,
you need to have those broken bonds.

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:11.420
Catalysis is good, but it also
means things are highly reactive

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:15.710
sometimes undesirably.
And that can lead to corrosion

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:35.086
which is undesirable.
Where is corrosion going to occur?

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.500
This material is not uniform in its
properties. The corrosion

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:09.000
resistance of an atom deep inside
the crystal is different from the

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.500
corrosion resistance on the free
surface, which is different from the

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:18.000
corrosion resistance along this
internal surface.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.500
Each of these regions is called a
grain. The grain is a virtual

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:27.000
single crystal. It is
a single crystal.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:33.000
We have a polycrystalline material
consisting of a tapestry of single

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:39.000
crystals called grains.
And this internal surface is called

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:45.000
a grain boundary.
Both of these are defects.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:51.000
What does the grain boundary do?
Well, the grain boundary does

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:57.000
several things.
First of all, the grain boundary

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:22.140
acts as a trap for impurities.
That can be good or it can be bad.

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:26.420
If all the impurities collect at
the grain boundaries,

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:30.710
and those impurities embrittle the
material, it doesn't matter what

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:34.990
ductility the grains have,
the material will fail at the grain

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:39.280
boundary. It would be as though you
had bricks that are very strong held

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:43.570
together by a weak mortar.
The grain boundaries act as that

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:47.850
mortar, but they have beneficial
effects. Imagine a dislocation

00:08:47.850 --> 00:08:52.660
sliding in one grain.
It wants to rip through the entire

00:08:52.660 --> 00:08:57.990
material. That misregistry of atoms
at the grain boundary stops the

00:08:57.990 --> 00:09:03.330
dislocation so it can act as a site
for arresting dislocations.

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:08.660
It arrests dislocations. I talked
to you last day about the management

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:13.990
of defects. If we want to have a
material that has high strength and

00:09:13.990 --> 00:09:19.330
is not going to easily slip,
do we want a material that has

00:09:19.330 --> 00:09:23.860
coarse grains or fine grains?
We want to have fine grain material.

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:27.590
Grain boundary engineering is
important in the management of the

00:09:27.590 --> 00:09:31.330
mechanical properties of material.
